column168: DMP RECIEVED A CALL FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE FLOOR ON THE PD8 FROM THE DOCK SUPERVISOR WHICH WAS DISCOVERED BY THE PICKOFF. THE BELT WAS SHUT OFF AND SUCURED AND THE AREA WAS EVACUATED. A DESIGNATED RESPONDER DONNING THE CORRECT PPE RESPONDED TO THE AREA WITHIN 5 MINUTES AND USING THE DECISION TREE, IDENTIFIED THE LEAKING PACKAGE AND CONTAINED IT. THE OUTER CARTON OF THE PACKAGE WAS VISIBLY STAINED ON THE BOTTOM AND THE SIDES BUT NOT LEAKING OUTSIDE ONTO THE SURROUNDING AREA. THE PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO THE DMP FOR PROCESSING AND FURTHER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT ONE OF THE INNER BLADDERS WAS PUNCTURED AND HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 12 OUNCES.

column168: On July 3, 2023, one (1) 55-gallon drum of nitric acid had a loosened lid and released approximately one half (0.5) gallon of product to the trailer interior. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works, Inc. (EWI) to remediate the site. Crews inspected the drum and suspected the seal on the lid was faulty. EWI utilized a forklift to place the drum into an over pack drum to be shipped back to the terminal for further evaluation. All released material was neutralized and recovered with absorbents. Impacted absorbents and PPE were placed into a poly liner and removed from the site for disposal.

column168: RESPONDER USED THE DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEET TO CONTAIN SPILL AND BRING IT BACK TO THE DMP CAGE FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.

On 7/11/2023 at approximately 1525, Dangerous Goods Adminstration received a call from Employee 780470 at international hub in Köln, Germany, reporting a flammable liquid spill.  The shipment consisted of 8 fiberboad boxes, each with one metal can inside.  One of the shipments was discovered to have leaked onto one other shipment.  The cause of the spillage was undetermined. German policy on spills requires a call to the fire brigade, who then took possession of the both the leaking package and the affected pakcage.

Package was offered to a spill clean up specialist located at our Memphis Hub location.  During night time sort operations, ULD was opened to find a puddle under a large package.  Package had fibreboard strapped to a pallet and labeled as an overpack.  This over pack was covering 2 blue plastic drum containing 200 L of product.  It was seen that during travel, a small hole developed on the bottom of one of the drums allowing for an estimated 3L of product to escape.  It is not known when or how the hole developed.  Hole was patched before drum was placed in a salvage drum. and shipper contacted for an amended shipper's declaration.

column168: During off loading, technicians at the receiving facility observed a cubic yard fiberboard container of hazardous debris was smoldering. The debris was contaminated with acetone and methyl ethyl ketone. The technicians isolated the container to an area of the receiving pad and extinguished with an ABC extinguisher. The contents were repacked to a new container and dry ice was added. The repackaged material was scanned with an RFID camera and determined not to have an elevated temperature.  While unloading the remaining containers of debris, technicians found that a drum of methyl methacrylate had partially released some of its contents. The material solidified as expanded foam. The solidified material was repackaged and sampled for analysis. All containers on the trailer were imaged with RFID camera and found to not exhibit elevated temperatures.   No materials were released.
column169: The incident is in investigation. The generator is implementing corrective actions.

column168: Lone Star Hazmat Response was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor’s arrival, personnel observed that the released material impacted a 5ft-by-5ft area of the trailer floor and a 2ft-by-2ft area of asphalt yard.  Lone Star Hazmat Response personnel estimated that  five (5) gallons of material was released due to  loose caps on almost  all the 1-gallon plastic jugs on the pallet. Lone Star Hazmat Response personnel removed all the plastic jugs from the cardboard packaging and verified that all the  jugs were impacted from the pallet.  Lone Star Hazmat Response deployed Sodium Bicarbonate to neutralize the impacted areas and then placed down Oil Dri as an absorbent. The spent material was gathered and placed into two 55-gallon poly drums along with the impacted cardboard. The impacted 1-gallon plastic jugs were containerized into two 95-gallon poly drums and two (2) 55-gallon poly drums. The generated waste was labeled and staged in a secure location onsite at the terminal prior to the contractor demobilization. The generated waste will remain onsite for the ESTES DGRM team to coordinate disposal.

column168: On 07/13/2023 at aprroximatley 1255, Dangerous Goods Administration received a call from Employee 3989104 at the ramp faclity in Mirabel, reporting an undeclared matches shipment.  The shipment consisted of one fiberboard box, containing several packets of safety matches.  The shipment was discovered due to an insecure closure.  The outer package was resused and worn and the tape failed keep the package closed.  The package was prepared  in accordance with the required marking, labeling, packaging, and paperwork.  The shipment is being held, pending an investigation in the Canadian regulatory entity.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Reclosing
column168: While loading the IBC into a van trailer, a Veolia operator noticed the IBC had leaked nearly a gallon of waste on to the ground. The leak appeared to be coming from a outlet on the bottom of the valve. The valve would have to fail for this to happen. The outlet was plugged with spill pads temporarily to contain the leak and the waste was transferred in to another tote for continued transportation to the disposal facility.
column169: Veolia will retrain personnel on container inspection prior to shipment from the customer. However, please note,  the valve did not fail until it was on the dock at Veolia 10 day intransit facility in Baytown, TX. There was no failure of the tote while the package was in public transportation. The Veolia crew who picked up the package from the shipper would have never known the valve was going to fail but the container did appear to be aged.

On July 13, 2023, one (1) 446-gallon tote containing isopropanol experienced a faulty valve and released approximately one-half (.5) gallon of product to the concrete. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Miller Environmental Group (MEG) to remediate the impacted surface. Crews utilized absorbent pads to remove residual products and insure cleaning of the impacted tote. Poly sheeting was placed around the tote as a precautionary measure. Upon further inspection of the value it was determined that a part would need to be order to repair the tote. Crews transferred the contents of the tote into nine (9) 55-gallon drums to be collected the following day. All spent absorbents, damaged pails, and impacted cardboard box were collected and containerized into one (1) 55-gallon poly bag for transport and disposal. After receiving approval from on-site RLC representative, Mr. Eric Tisdale, MEG crews secured the site and scheduled their return at a later date to replace the valve and transfer the contents of the tote.
NO COMMENTS PROVIDED

QA TYLER GRABBED YELLOW HAZMAT DRUMS TO PUT THE LEAKING HAZMAT INTO WHILE USING PROPER SAFETY EQUIPMENT. NO CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED DUE TO LEAKAGE ONLY ON BOX. DescribePack: THE BOX HAD IN TWO DIFFERENT CORNERS WET/CORROSION SPOTS DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: QUICK RESPONSIVENESS, CONTAINING THE DAMAGE IN THE YELLOW HAZMAT DRUM.

SequenceEvent: THE PACKAGE ARRIVED IN THE QA AREA THE PACKAGE WAS NOTICABLY WET AND TORN UPON INSPECTION IT WAS DEEMED A FULLY REGULATED HAZMAT IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT ALL 4 1 GAL JUGS HAD FAILED DUE TO POOR INNER PACKAGING AND LOOSE LIDS. DescribePack: THE PACKAGE FAILED AT THE TOP DUE TO POOR CLOSURES AND AT THE BODY DUE TO POOR INNER PACKAGING DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: ONCE DEEMED A FULLY REGULATED HAZMAT IT WAS SEGREGATED FROM OTHERS

SequenceEvent: The package was sent to QA for inspection due to the box being wet. DescribePack: Upon inspection found the contents had a loose cap causing the leak. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: Fold absorb was used to mitigate the release.

SequenceEvent: PACKAGE HANDLER NOTICED WETTNESS ON THE BOX AND IMMEDIATLY CALLED FOR SORT MANAGER PAUL. ONCE PAUL INVESTIGATED, HE CALLED QA ON THE RADIO TO COME HELP WITH THE REMOVAL OF THE DAMAGED HAZMAT. QA TYLER USED PROPER SAFETY EQUIPMENT AND A YELLOW SALVAGE DRUM TO MITIGATE THE DAMAGE. NO CLEANUP NEEDED, LEAKAGE STAYED ON BOX. DescribePack: BOX HAD LEAKAGE ALL ON THE CORNER OF THE BOX, CAP WAS LOOSE AND LEAKED INTERNALLY. DurationRel: 2 and MitigateEffect: USING SAFETY EQUIPMENT SUCH AS GLOVES, APRON, GLASSES & GETTING THE SALVAGE DRUM TO CONTAIN ANY ADDITIONAL SPILL.

column168: XPO Logistics terminal UPH experienced a UN3105 NOROX MEKP-900 release from 8 boxes each containing (4) 1-gallon poly jugs. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. Contractors arrived onsite and confirmed approximately 1-gallon of product released impacting their boxes and dock floor in a 3' x 3' due to loose lids on the jugs. A total of 32 bottles were found damaged and containerized into a 30-gallon and 55-gallon vented poly drums. Absorbent pads were utilized to clean the released product. The impacted rags, cardboard, and cleanup debris were then placed into a separate 55-gallon vented poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

Veolia employee were loading the IBC onto a trailer at the 10 day intransit facility in Menomonee Falls, WI when a leak was identified as coming from the bottom valve of the container. Upon further inspection, the valve completely snapped off resulting in a release of approximately 25 gallons of material onto the trailer floor and to the pavement beneath the trailer. The spill was quickly cleaned up and the remaining material in the IBC was transferred into a 55 gallon drum.  The NRC was notified to report the release of a D003 material that exceed the RQ limit of 100 lbs.
column169: Veolia operators were reminded that all containers should be inspected prior to handling to assess for any damage and make sure all components are in good condition.

column168: On June 13, 2023, two (2) 5-liter metal cans of UN1263 were crushed during transit and released approximately one quarter (.25) gallon of product to the pallet in the trailer. R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from HazChem Environmental (HCE) to remediate the impacted surfaces. HCE personnel downstacked the pallet to find two (2) leaking cans of product.  Crews wiped down the impacted freight with universal absorbent pads, and then they staged the remediated freight for further shipment and processing. The leaking cans and miscellaneous cleanup debris were placed into one (1) 55-gallon drum that was staged in the terminal's waste holding room. Crews took the impacted pallet back to their shop for reuse.

R+L Carriers retained Cura Emergency Services, LC who dispatched a crew from Valley Environmental Response (VER) to remediate the impacted site.  VER personnel deployed absorbents and a neutralizing agent to remediate the site. All spent absorbents were collected and containerized into three (3) cubic yard boxes. All containers were staged onsite for disposal by R+L

column42: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column168: DESCRIPTION: A 40ft ocean container caught fire while in transit storage prior to loading at the CSX ramp in Norfolk, Virginia. The fire was caused by undeclared and improperly packaged Lithium Ion Batteries (EV Vehicle Batteries). The container was loaded at a facility in St Louis, Missouri, chosen by the shipper. However, the shipping documents provided by the shipper to Apex Logistics, declared the commodity as "Copper Flakes" and not dangerous goods. RESPONSE: Upon notification of the fire, Apex Logistics International LLC informed the steamship line CMA CGM that there could be undeclared dangerous goods in all the containers from this shipper. 24 containers from this shipper were in Norfolk, VA.  INVESTIGATION: A surveyor has inspected the containers, and out of the 24 containers, all 24 of them have been identified to contain some form of dangerous goods, specifically batteries either class 9 or class 8. Some of the containers, contained D/D/R Lithium Batteries that were correctly packed according to the 49 CFR, however at least 4 containers contained unpacked Recycled Lithium Batteries (EV Batteries).  CORRECTIVE ACTIONS: Due to the severity and complexity of the incident, the shipper, Zhiyun Sports LLC, has authorized Apex Logistics International LLC to arrange the pickup, storage, and return of the containers. Apex Logistics has contracted a hazardous materials emergency service (Hepaco) to assist in the offloading and safe storage of these dangerous goods.
column169: Apex Logistics International is not the shipper, however the shipper has been made aware of the correct reference to packaging and preparation in accordance with the 49 CFR. In addition this shipper has been blacklisted from shipping with Apex Logistics International.  Apex will continue to develop its Know Your Customer (KYC) training, in order to better vet potential violators of the 49 CFR.  In addition, we will attempt to identify shippers and consignees related to the recycling business to reduce the likelihood of undeclared Battery Shipments.   There currently is an open investigation on this incident from the DOT.

column168: On 7/17/2023 a Veolia employee was loading drums from a trailer into another trailer at the Veolia, Schenectady, NY 10 day intransit facility. During the process, the employee punctured a 55-gallon steel drum with the drum cart while placing it in an outbound trailer. The employee was moving the drums into the trailer and misjudged the distance to the drum piercing it with the forks of the drum cart and caused a leak from the drum. About a gallon of liquid leaked out of the impacted drum. The drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon salvage drum, the spill cleaned up, and transportation to the ultimate disposal facility was continued without further incident. The duration of release is anticipated to be less than 1 minute as the employee noticed the accident right away.
column169: On 7/17/2023 the Veolia safety manager was notified of the spill. The results of the investigation revealed that the employee simply misjudged the distance from the corner of the pallet to the nearby drum that was hit. The hole was on the bottom of the drum. The employee removed himself from duty and left Veolia for the day. The employee was subsequently terminated after not showing up for work for a week.

column168: SequenceEvent: The hazmat pkg was on a closure cart in the middle area by our chutes where the closures and misloads go. I had checked on the package earlier to see where it needed to go, and did not see any leaking around the package. Someone had grabbed the cart that the package was on, and put it on the rollers attached to the chute, and about 30 minutes later, I heard the manager call out that there was a leaking Hazmat. I ran over to the area, and the manager, a PH, and another QA were picking up the leaking, corrosive Hazmat with their bare hands, putting it into a tote, and making the package leak everywhere. I immediately told them to set the package down and to clear the area. I let them know that it was a corrosive liquid and that it could burn them. They had already set it on the tugger, and it was leaking all over the back of the tugger as well. They set it down, and I grabbed it, and put it on my QA cart. When I set it on the cart, the liquid splashed up on my arms and on my left leg (as I was wearing shorts), and it started burning my skin. I told them to immediately clear the area, go rinse their hands, and I took my cart to the QA area, and hurried to the Hazmat shower to start rinsing my arms and leg off. After I had rinsed off for about 8 to 10 mins, I then went back and got the tugger that had been leaked on, and took it to the QA area to put it out of order. I then took my QA cart to the Hazmat cage and put the damaged portion of the package into a lined salvage drum. DescribePack: Package failed due to a loose cap on one of the bottles of Warewashing Detergents. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: I went to the spill area, and put the chemical neutralizer onto the spilled liquid and then put the shredded absorbing material onto it as well. I put caution tape over the area, and the next morning, I pH tested several spots, as well as the spots on the tugger, and then put down more neutralizer as needed. I then waited until about 11:00a that morning to sweep up the neutralizer and absorbing material into a hazardous material bag, and place it into the salvage drum with the other damaged portion of the damaged package.

7-11-23: At approx 2100 hrs, in Morgantown WV our truck / trailer carrying UN,2312, Phenol, Molten, 6.1, II was flagged down. A mist from the top of the tanker trailer had landed on a car following our TT; Due to the HM product, EMS was activated. Fire, Police and HM responded. There was an light odor of the product in the air. A check of a valve at the top of the tanker revealed that hit was not fully closed. The driver had performed a pre trip inspection and the valve was closed at that time. No product was exiting the tank at this time. The product, which is not under pressure, would only be able to exit that valve while ascending or descending inclines. On flat ground the product· would not be able to be released. The valve was secured by HM Responders. The tanker was allowed to complete the remainder of the trip ( Approx 1/2 mile) to be unloaded. Two passerbys claimed to be affected by the product. They were transported to a local hospital for observations, then released. C Three Logistics has contracted with a HM response cleanup operation to properly decontaminate the exterior of the affected motor vehicle.
column169: C Three Logistics will be communicating with and working with the shipper, in order to ensure that their loading operators and our drivers are aware of the importance of properly securing the valve and to ensure that the safety measures are properly adhered to. This was a "no touch" load for our driver. The shipper is to load and secure the valves, the receiver is to unload and secure the valves.

She then tells me it was warm. Flight Attendant tells the passenger"We need to take it out of the trash cart now", which we did. Flight Attendant calls the Capt back and told him the Vape was warm and if he wants me to put it in a bucket of ice water. He instructs me to place it in the fire containment bag. Flight Attendant followed the procedures for this and placed it in a cart. The passenger and Flight Attendant walked out of the aircraft together and the Flight Attendant handed the bag to the Agent. The remediation work is complete pending final sample analysis and report.
column169: We have and will continue to train drivers about this particularly dangerous stretch of road. This training includes reducing speed, maintaining full control! of CMV and rollover prevention training.  Other suggestions: This stretch of 126 between mm 60 and 63 westbound is an extremely dangerous stretch of road. The roadway is poorly designed and the superelevation of the curve versus the shoulder amplifies small errors into major accidents.

column168: On July 2, 2023 at approximately 7:15 PM, a Plains transport driver with a load of crude oil was traveling southbound on State Highway 42 in Gregg County, TX. At the intersection of Hwy 42 and Texaco Rd, a 2012 Nissan traveling east on Texaco Rd failed to stop at a stop sign and collided with Plains transport, causing the tank trailer to separate from the tractor and roll over into the ditch. Upon separation, the landing gear broke off and punctured a 3x3 inch hole in the trailer, at the 7 o'clock position if upright, but upon roll over, puncture was located at the 10 o'clock position.  As a result of the collision, 70 gallons of diesel from the transport fuel tank and approximately 2 gallons of hydraulic fluid, from the trailer hydraulic pump and lines, were released to the roadway and roadside ditch. The Plains vehicle and the other vehicle were non drivable and had to be towed from the scene. An absorbent was applied to the roadway to encapsulate the diesel and hydraulic fluid, then swept and contained in 55 gallon drums. The impacted roadside ditch has been excavated to remove impacted soil and manifested for disposal, in accordance with TCEQ clean-up criteria. . .  The Plains employee was injured and treated at a medical facility. Occupant of other vehicle perished at the scene.
column169: No recommendations or actions were taken, as not deemed necessary due to Plains following DOT guidelines and not at fault for this incident.
